HashSet in Java
`HashSet` is a class in `java.util` that implements Set, Collection, and Iterable.
It is backed internally by a `HashMap` and stores unique elements only.

Key Characteristics
- No duplicates allowed.
- No guaranteed order of elements (unlike `TreeSet` or `LinkedHashSet`).
- Allows null element (only one).
- Provides constant-time performance for add, remove, contains, and size operations (on average).
- Not synchronized (use `Collections.synchronizedSet()` for thread safety).
Categorized Methods
1. Adding Elements
●	`add(E e)` – Adds element if not already present.
●	`addAll(Collection c)` – Adds all elements from another collection.
2. Accessing Elements
●	Direct access by index is **not supported** (unlike `List`).
●	Use iteration methods to traverse.
3. Removing Elements
●	`remove(Object o)` – Removes specified element if present.
●	`removeAll(Collection c)` – Removes all elements in given collection.
●	`clear()` – Removes all elements.
●	`retainAll(Collection c)` – Retains only elements present in given collection.
4. Searching & Checking
●	`contains(Object o)` – Checks if element exists.
●	`containsAll(Collection c)` – Checks if all exist.
●	`isEmpty()` – Checks if empty.
●	`size()` – Returns number of elements.
●	`equals(Object o)` – Compares with another set.
●	`hashCode()` – Returns hash code.
5. Iteration Methods
●	`iterator()` – Returns iterator.
●	`forEach(Consumer action)` – Performs action for each element.
●	`spliterator()` – Returns spliterator.
6. Conversion Methods
●	`toArray()` – Converts to array.
●	`toArray(T[] a)` – Converts to typed array.
7. Cloning
●	`clone()` – Creates shallow copy.
Java Code Demonstration

import java.util.*;

public class HashSetDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();

        // 1. Adding Elements
        set.add("A");
        set.add("B");
        set.add("C");
        set.addAll(Arrays.asList("D", "E", "F"));

        // 2. Accessing Elements (via iteration)
        for (String s : set) {
            System.out.println(s);
        }

        // 3. Removing Elements
        set.remove("C");
        set.removeAll(Arrays.asList("D", "E"));
        set.retainAll(Arrays.asList("A", "B"));
        set.clear();

        // 4. Searching & Checking
        set.addAll(Arrays.asList("X", "Y", "Z"));
        System.out.println(set.contains("X"));
        System.out.println(set.containsAll(Arrays.asList("X", "Y")));
        System.out.println(set.isEmpty());
        System.out.println(set.size());
        System.out.println(set.equals(new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList("X", "Y", "Z"))));
        System.out.println(set.hashCode());

        // 5. Iteration
        Iterator<String> it = set.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) System.out.println(it.next());

        set.forEach(System.out::println);
        Spliterator<String> spl = set.spliterator();
        spl.forEachRemaining(System.out::println);

        // 6. Conversion
        Object[] arr = set.toArray();
        String[] strArr = set.toArray(new String[0]);

        // 7. Cloning
        HashSet<String> cloned = (HashSet<String>) set.clone();
        System.out.println("Cloned HashSet: " + cloned);
    }
}

